## How It Works

HTTP polling is a request-response model where the client repeatedly asks the server for new data at fixed intervals. Every poll is a full HTTP request with headers, TLS handshake overhead (if not keep-alive), and server processing — even when nothing has changed. This creates three problems: latency (data waits up to the poll interval), wasted bandwidth (empty responses), and server load (handling requests that return no useful data).

WebSockets solve this with a protocol upgrade. The client sends an HTTP Upgrade request, and the server responds with 101 Switching Protocols. After the upgrade, both sides share a persistent TCP connection that supports bidirectional messaging. Either side can send data at any time without initiating a new request. The server pushes messages the instant they arrive — no polling delay.

The communication model shifts from client-initiated pull to server-initiated push. The client opens one connection and receives a stream of messages. This reduces latency from poll-interval-bounded (2 seconds in the example) to network-propagation-bounded (typically 10-100ms).

The trade-off appears in operations. HTTP requests are stateless — any server can handle any request. WebSockets are stateful — the connection is bound to a specific server instance. Load balancers need sticky sessions or connection-aware routing. If the server crashes, the client must detect the disconnect and reconnect, implementing retry logic and potentially losing in-flight messages.

## Code Example

```javascript
// Polling approach (problematic)
async function pollMessages() {
  while (true) {
    const response = await fetch('/api/messages?since=' + lastTimestamp)
    const messages = await response.json()
    if (messages.length > 0) {
      renderMessages(messages)
      lastTimestamp = messages[messages.length - 1].timestamp
    }
    await sleep(2000) // 2-second polling interval
  }
}

// WebSocket approach (better)
const ws = new WebSocket('wss://chat.example.com')

ws.onopen = () => {
  console.log('Connection established')
}

ws.onmessage = (event) => {
  const message = JSON.parse(event.data)
  renderMessages([message])
}

ws.onclose = () => {
  // Reconnect logic required
  setTimeout(connectWebSocket, 1000)
}

// Server-side (Node.js with ws library)
const WebSocket = require('ws')
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 8080 })

wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
  // Push messages instantly when they arrive
  messageBroker.on('new-message', (msg) => {
    ws.send(JSON.stringify(msg))
  })
})
```

## Key Points

- **Latency**: Polling delays delivery by up to the poll interval; WebSockets deliver instantly
- **Bandwidth**: Polling sends full HTTP headers every interval; WebSockets send only the payload
- **Statefulness**: HTTP is stateless and horizontally scalable; WebSockets bind to a server instance
- **Connection management**: WebSockets require heartbeat/ping-pong to detect dead connections
- **Fallback**: Some networks block WebSockets; implementations should fall back to long-polling

## Common Mistake

The most common mistake is treating WebSockets as fire-and-forget. Developers open a connection and assume it stays alive forever. In practice, network changes, server restarts, and load balancer timeouts silently kill connections. Without reconnection logic and message acknowledgment, messages are silently lost. A production WebSocket client must implement exponential backoff reconnection, message IDs for deduplication, and a heartbeat mechanism (typically ping every 30 seconds) to keep the connection alive through proxies and firewalls.

## Interview Tip

The interviewer is testing whether you understand the fundamental shift from pull to push, and whether you recognize the operational trade-offs. A good answer explains why WebSockets reduce latency. A great answer also addresses connection lifecycle management, horizontal scaling challenges with sticky sessions, and when polling is actually preferable (low-frequency updates, simple APIs, stateless infrastructure). Mentioning fallback strategies (long-polling, SSE) shows production awareness.
